[11:31.41] [Scattering flowers]
[11:32.78] I hoped thou shouldst have been my Hamlet's wife;
[11:35.32] I thought thy bride-bed to have deck'd, sweet maid,
[11:39.48] And not have strew'd thy grave.
[11:41.85]LAERTES O, treble woe
[11:43.65] Fall ten times treble on that cursed head,
[11:47.49] Whose wicked deed thy most ingenious sense
[11:50.42] Deprived thee of! Hold off the earth awhile,
[11:54.70] Till I have caught her once more in mine arms:
[11:57.68] [Leaps into the grave]
[11:58.30] Now pile your dust upon the quick and dead,
[12:04.82] Till of this flat a mountain you have made,
[12:07.43] To o'ertop old Pelion, or the skyish head
[12:10.22] Of blue Olympus.
[12:11.53]HAMLET [Advancing] What is he whose grief
[12:12.65] Bears such an emphasis? whose phrase of sorrow
[12:15.63] Conjures the wandering stars, and makes them stand
[12:18.37] Like wonder-wounded hearers? This is I,
[12:20.60] Hamlet the Dane.
[12:22.34] [Leaps into the grave]
[12:22.84]LAERTES The devil take thy soul!
[12:25.32] [Grappling with him]
[12:25.63]HAMLET Thou pray'st not well.
[12:26.63] I prithee, take thy fingers from my throat;
[12:31.29] For, though I am not splenitive and rash,
[12:32.96] Yet have I something in me dangerous,
[12:34.89] Which let thy wiseness fear: hold off thy hand.
[12:37.50]KING CLAUDIUS Pluck them asunder.
[12:39.17]QUEEN GERTRUDE Hamlet, Hamlet!
[12:41.66]All Gentlemen,--
[12:43.58]HORATIO Good my lord, be quiet.
[12:44.88] [The Attendants part them, and they come out of the grave]
[12:45.51]HAMLET Why I will fight with him upon this theme
[12:46.87] Until my eyelids will no longer wag.
[12:49.04]QUEEN GERTRUDE O my son, what theme?
[12:50.93]HAMLET I loved Ophelia: forty thousand brothers
[12:56.31] Could not, with all their quantity of love,
[12:58.05] Make up my sum. What wilt thou do for her?
[13:01.71]KING CLAUDIUS O, he is mad, Laertes.
[13:03.76]QUEEN GERTRUDE For love of God, forbear him.
